• Antibiotics used in the treatment of pyogenic liver abscess include:
  penicillins eg, ampicillin;
  β-lactam/β-lactamase inhibitor eg, piperacillin/tazobactam and ticarcillin/clavulanic acid;
  3rd-generation cephalosporins eg, ceftriaxone; 
  aminoglycosides eg, gentamicin;
  fluoroquinolones eg, ciprofloxacin and levofloxacin;
  carbapenems eg, imipenem-cilastatin, meropenem, doripenem, and ertapenem;
  lincosamide eg, clindamycin; 
  glycopeptide antibiotics eg, vancomycin.

• Systemic antibiotics are used in patients with severe periodontal infections ie, periodontal abscesses, necrotizing 
gingivitis, periodontitis, or if there is fever or regional lymphadenopathy, or if the infection has spread to the bony 
cortex and surrounding soft tissue.
• Some antibiotics used for periodontal infections include:
  Penicillins eg, amoxicillin in combination with clavulanic acid, ampicillin in combination with sulbactam, and 
benzylpenicillin;
  Cephalosporins eg, cefalexin and cefuroxime;
  Quinolones eg, ciprofloxacin and levofloxacin;
  Macrolides eg, azithromycin, erythromycin, and spiramycin;
  Tetracyclines eg, doxycycline;
  Other antibiotics eg, clindamycin and metronidazole.

Doses are based on individual drug doses. For specific brand dosing, refer to approved product information in your country.
  Other cephalosporins that may be used in the treatment of pneumonia include: 
 – First-generation eg, cefadroxil and cefazolin;
 – Second-generation eg, cefaclor, cefamandole, cefmetazole, cefminox, cefotiam, cefoxitin, cefprozil;
 – Third-generation eg, cefdinir, cefditoren, cefetamet, cefixime, cefoperazone, cefotaxime, cefpirome, 
ceftazidime, ceftibuten, ceftizoxime, ceftriaxone, and latamoxef; 
 – Fourth-generation eg, cefepime and cefpirome;
 – Fifth-generation eg, ceftaroline ceftobiprole, ceftozolane, and fosamil.

• Patients with a non-functioning or inaccessible GI tract who require nutritional support receive nutrients directly 
into the venous system, either into a central vein or a peripheral vein.
• Several parenteral nutritional solutions are available and are chosen based on patient’s underlying medical 
condition and patient’s age. These contain: 
  Carbohydrates eg, dextrose; 
  Fats eg, omega-3 fatty acids (eicosapentaenoic acid and docosahexaenoic acid), refined soy bean extract, 
olive oil, fish oil, and triglycerides;
  Proteins eg, dipeptides, amino acids (eg, alanine, arginine, aspartic acid, cysteine, glutamic acid, glycine, 
histidine, isoleucine, leucine, lysine, methionine, phenylalanine, proline, serine, taurine, threonine, tryptophan, 
tyrosine, and valine);
  Electrolytes eg, calcium, chloride, magnesium, phosphorus, potassium, and sodium;
  Minerals and trace elements eg, chromium, copper, fluoride, iodine, iron, manganese, selenium, and zinc;
  Vitamins eg, ascorbic acid, retinol, vitamin B complex, vitamin D, vitamin E, and vitamin K.

Doses are based on individual drug doses. For specific brand dosing, refer to approved product information in your country.
  Aminoglycosides eg, amikacin, dibekacin, gentamicin, kanamycin, netilmicin, streptomycin, and tobramycin;
  Chloramphenicols eg, chloramphenicol and thiamphenicol;
  Sulfonamides eg, sulfamethoxazole (especially in combination with trimethoprim), sulfadiazine, 
sulfadimidine, and sulfamerazine;
  Tetracyclines eg, chlortetracycline, doxycycline, minocycline, oxytetracycline, tigecycline, and tetracycline;
  Other antibiotics, eg, clindamycin, fosfomycin, fusidic acid, lincomycin, linezolid, metronidazole, pristinamycin, 
rifampicin, and vancomycin;
  Other β-lactams eg, aztreonam, cilastatin, ertapenem, imipenem, and meropenem.
• Antibacterial combinations eg, co-trimoxazole (sulfamethoxazole and trimethoprim) and co-trimazine (sulfadiazine 
and trimethoprim), are commonly used to prevent inactivation of the active drug by enzymes in the bacteria. The 
accompanying drug usually has a certain degree of antibacterial activity, but is mostly used for its action against 
the degrading enzyme.
• Counseling Tip: Take the entire course of prescribed medications, particularly antibiotics. Stopping the intake 
of medication too soon can cause the illness to reoccur and contributes to the development of antibioticresistant bacteria.

